# 10. Risks and mitigations

| **Risk** | **Severity** | **Mitigation** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Big tech ships similar product | High | Speed to market + open protocol creates switching cost. Community playbooks are a moat they cannot replicate. |
| LLM API costs spike | Medium | Multi-provider routing means we can shift to cheaper models instantly. BYOK plan insulates us. |
| Screen control unreliable | Medium | Three-mode fallback (API > CLI > Screen). Invest in visual memory to improve over time. |
| Security breach / API key leak | High | AES-256 vault, OS keychain, granular permissions, signed playbooks, audit trail. |
| Low marketplace adoption | Medium | Seed with 50+ free high-quality playbooks. Partner with automation influencers. |
| Single developer bottleneck | High | AI pair programming accelerates output 5–10x. Modular architecture allows parallel work streams. |

# 11. Immediate next steps

Phase 1 begins now. The first three deliverables are:

- Set up the project repository with Python backend structure, Tauri shell, and React frontend scaffold.

- Implement the LLM Gateway with LiteLLM integration, basic task classifier, and cost tracking.

- Build Telegram bot integration that receives commands and executes them via CLI executor.

Target for first working demo: a Telegram message triggers the agent to run a shell command on the PC and return the result. This proves the core loop: message in, brain decides, action executes, result out.

| **The bottom line** AgentOS combines three billion-dollar ideas into one product: an autonomous PC agent, an intelligent LLM router, and a community marketplace for automation. Each component has standalone value. Together, they create a platform that no single company has built. The open protocol drives adoption. The closed core protects value. The marketplace creates a flywheel. And the whole thing installs with a double-click. |
